 Here's one way to find the common elements in two arrays without using any extra data structures:
```
function commonElements(arr1, arr2) {
  let result = [];
  for (let i = 0; i < arr1.length; i++) {
    for (let j = 0; j < arr2.length; j++) {
      if (arr1[i] === arr2[j]) {
        result.push(arr1[i]);
      }
    }
  }
  return result;
}
```
This function uses two nested loops to compare each element in the first array with each element in the second array. If the two elements are the same, the function adds the common element to the result array.

Here's an example of how the function would work:
```
const arr1 = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5];
const arr2 = [2, 3, 4, 5, 6];

console.log(commonElements(arr1, arr2)); // Output: [2, 3, 4, 5]
```
This function has a time complexity of O(n^2), which is not very efficient for large arrays. However, it does not use any extra data structures, which makes it a simple solution.

Here's a more efficient solution that uses a single loop and a hash set to keep track of the common elements:
```
function commonElements(arr1, arr2) {
  const set = new Set();
  for (let i = 0; i < arr1.length; i++) {
    set.add(arr1[i]);
    set.add(arr2[i]);
  }
  return [...set].filter((x, i) => arr1.includes(x) && arr2.includes(x));
}
```
This function uses a hash set to keep track of the common elements between the two arrays. It adds each element in the arrays to the set, and then uses the `filter` method to remove any duplicates and return the common elements.

The time complexity of this function is O(n log n), which is more efficient than the previous solution for large arrays.
